        "urn": "urn:li:activity:7236972579855491072",
        "text": "\ud83d\udce2 New Policy Brief \ud83d\udc49 Data, when made accessible and re-used responsibly, is at the core of social and economic development, and technological innovation -including artificial intelligence.. yet current data governance efforts to unlock data are fragmented and siloed, and have failed to meaningfully advance data stewardship. \n\n\u2705 This policy brief suggests a pathway forward: an International Decade for Data (2025-2035) under G20 sponsorship that could bridge and accelerate current efforts. \u27a1\ufe0f Full version at: https://lnkd.in/ePhKAz8h\n\n\u27a1\ufe0f By fostering collaboration among diverse stakeholders\u2014governments, private sector, civil society, and academia\u2014the IDD aims to create a more unified approach to data governance. \n\n\u270d\ufe0f Co-authors: my colleagues David Passarelli, Muznah Siddiqui and Lorrayne Porciuncula\n\n\ud83e\udd14 Yet, a policy brief is only as good as its adoption \ud83d\udc49 Are leaders meeting for the G20 (Brasil) and the UN (Summit of the Future) serious about addressing today's data and data governance divide? \n\n\ud83d\udcbb See also: Unlocking the Potential: The Call for an International Decade of Data at: https://lnkd.in/eKPg7ZrA\n\n\n#DataGovernance #Innovation #SustainableDevelopment #IDD #G20 #DigitalTransformation #SummitofTheFuture"
